<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="space-y-6">
<div>
<h3>How do California wines differ from French wines?</h3>
<p>California wines typically show riper fruit flavors, higher alcohol content, and more upfront accessibility compared to French wines. French wines often emphasize terroir expression and require more aging to develop complexity, while California wines focus on varietal character and immediate appeal.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What's the best California wine region for beginners?</h3>
<p>Sonoma County offers the best introduction to California wine diversity. The region produces approachable styles across multiple varietals, offers excellent value compared to Napa, and provides easy tasting room access. Russian River Valley Pinot Noir and Dry Creek Valley Zinfandel are particularly beginner-friendly.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Why are California wines more expensive than other American wines?</h3>
<p>Land costs in premium California regions like Napa Valley can exceed $300,000 per acre. Additionally, longer growing seasons, hand harvesting, premium oak aging, and strong international demand drive prices higher than other American wine regions.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How long can California wines age?</h3>
<p>Premium California Cabernet Sauvignon can age 15-25 years or more, while Chardonnay typically peaks within 5-10 years. Zinfandel varies widely - some age beautifully for decades while others are best consumed within 5-7 years. Pinot Noir generally improves for 8-12 years.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What should I expect to pay for quality California wine?</h3>
<p>Excellent California wines start around $25-35 from established regions. Premium Napa Cabernet ranges from $50-150, while exceptional bottles can reach $200+. Central Coast regions offer outstanding value, with many excellent wines under $40.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Do California wines need decanting?</h3>
<p>Young California Cabernet Sauvignon and other tannic reds benefit from 30-60 minutes of decanting to soften tannins and open aromatics. Older wines may need careful decanting to separate sediment. Most white wines and lighter reds don't require decanting.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What's the difference between single vineyard and blended California wines?</h3>
<p>Single vineyard wines showcase specific site characteristics and terroir expression, often commanding higher prices for their uniqueness. Blended wines combine grapes from multiple vineyards to achieve consistency and complexity, typically offering better value and reliability across vintages.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Are organic California wines worth seeking out?</h3>
<p>Organic certification doesn't guarantee superior quality, but many organic California producers focus on sustainable farming that can enhance grape quality. The dry California climate makes organic farming more feasible than in humid regions, often resulting in expressive, terroir-driven wines.</p>
</div>
